        <hl1>Bush vs. Gore, Round 1: Now the People Debate; Third- Party Exclusion</hl1>
      </hedline>
      <abstract>
        <p>Zach Fried letter, commenting on presidential debate, scores exclusion of third-party candidate Ralph Nader</p>
      </abstract>
    </body.head>
    <body.content>
      <block class="lead_paragraph">
        <p>To the Editor:</p>
        <p>Tuesday night's mediocre effort on the part of Al Gore and George W. Bush to engage in meaningful dialogue was exactly what America was hoping not to hear (front page, Oct. 4).</p>
      </block>
      <block class="full_text">
        <p>To the Editor:</p>
        <p>Tuesday night's mediocre effort on the part of Al Gore and George W. Bush to engage in meaningful dialogue was exactly what America was hoping not to hear (front page, Oct. 4).</p>
        <p>Instead of honest debate and discussion, viewers saw two contenders sparring in an arena of vague proposals and lofty, indistinct promises.</p>
        <p>By excluding significant third-party candidates, the Commission on Presidential Debates, in my opinion, is not fulfilling its obligation to the voters of this country.</p>
        <p>Democracy requires open debate. An incomplete contest like Tuesday night's is surest way to ensure an election in which eligible voters will not go to the polls.</p>
        <p>ZACH FRIED  Brooklyn, Oct. 4, 2000</p>
      </block>
